{"author":{"id":"138b13306404778af60b1d60d606624fec41556ddac480b2d5f762806ce84fed"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782958624,"nonce":"sRWQoUtEu7gc+cAiAd04VtoLNbo=","kind":"spec","title":"kref CLI help \u0026 sane-defaults sweep — design","content_type":"text/markdown"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1782958624,"nonce":"pZriKOhjg4v5R49rFJEFNDPOelk=","body":"# kref CLI help \u0026 sane-defaults sweep — design\n\n**Date:** 2026-06-25\n**Status:** approved (brainstorming → ready for implementation plan)\n**Scope:** the argument-handling and help surface of every `kref` command.\nReplaces opaque cobra arg-count errors with actionable guidance, adds annotated\n`Example:` blocks to every leaf command, and gives the read-only inspection\ncommands a safe \"most-recently-modified\" default. No change to write or\ndestructive command semantics.\n\n## 1. Context\n\nRunning the CLI surfaces a paper cut that repeats across ~20 commands: invoking\na command without its required entry reference produces a bare, unactionable\nline. The root command sets `SilenceUsage: true` and `SilenceErrors: true`\n(`cmd/kref/main.go`), and the leaf commands rely on cobra's built-in arg\nvalidators (`cobra.ExactArgs`, `cobra.MinimumNArgs`). The result:\n\n```\n$ kref purge\nerror: accepts 1 arg(s), received 0\n```\n\nThe user is told *that* an argument is missing but not *what* to provide, *how*\nto find it, or *what the command would do*. The same opacity affects `show`,\n`log`, `diff`, `links`, `tree`, `rm`, `restore`, `resolve`, `edit`, `update`,\n`status`, `supersede`, `retier`, `promote`, `private`, `link add/rm`,\n`label add/rm`, and `ingest`.\n\nParent commands with subcommands (`label`, `link`, `sync`, `hooks`, `remote`)\nalready print their help when run bare — cobra's default for a command with no\n`RunE` — so they are not affected by the arg-error problem, only by the absence\nof examples.\n\nNo command currently carries an `Example:` field, so `kref \u003ccmd\u003e --help` never\nshows a worked invocation.\n\n## 2. Goals / non-goals\n\n**Goals**\n\n- Every command that needs an entry reference fails with an actionable error:\n  what is missing, how to find a valid value, and a worked example annotated\n  with what it does.\n- Every leaf command gains an `Example:` block so `--help` teaches by example.\n- The read-only inspection commands (`show`, `log`, `diff`, `links`, `tree`)\n  default to the most-recently-modified entry when given no id, announcing the\n  choice on stderr.\n- Error output stays tight: a mistake yields the short actionable error, not a\n  full cobra usage/flags dump. The complete reference remains one `--help` away.\n\n**Non-goals**\n\n- No new behavioral defaults for write or destructive commands. They never\n  guess an entry; they emit the actionable error.\n- No `$EDITOR`-on-empty ergonomics for `add`/`edit` (deferred; out of scope).\n- No change to JSON output shapes, flag names, or command grouping.\n- No change to parent-command behavior beyond adding examples.\n\n## 3. Mechanism\n\n### 3.1 Actionable arg errors\n\nA leaf command that requires an entry reference declares its guidance as data,\nand a shared helper turns a wrong arg count into the actionable error. The\nhelper returns a cobra `Args` validator so the error is produced *before*\n`RunE` runs, exactly where cobra's generic validators run today.\n\n```go\n// argGuide coaches the user when a command is invoked without the entry\n// reference(s) it needs. It is rendered by guidedArgs into the actionable\n// error; the same examples feed the command's Example field (§3.2).\ntype argGuide struct {\n\tnoun     string   // what is missing, e.g. \"an entry id\", \"an old and a new id\"\n\tfind     string   // discovery command, e.g. \"kref list\"\n\tusage    string   // the canonical form, e.g. \"kref purge \u003cid\u003e\"\n\texamples []string // worked invocations, each \"cmd  # what it does\"\n}\n\n// guidedArgs wraps an exact/min arg count with argGuide coaching. On the wrong\n// count it returns the actionable error; otherwise it defers to the inner\n// validator so all other validation is unchanged.\nfunc guidedArgs(inner cobra.PositionalArgs, g argGuide) cobra.PositionalArgs\n```\n\nRendered form (the steps the user asked for, plus the outcome-annotated\nexamples):\n\n```\n$ kref purge\nerror: purge needs an entry id.\n  find one:   kref list\n  then:       kref purge \u003cid\u003e\n  example:    kref purge a1b2c3d4        # delete the entry's ref\n              kref purge a1b2c3d4 --gc   # ...and gc objects now\n  details:    kref purge --help\n```\n\n`SilenceUsage` stays `true`, so the custom error is the entire output. The\nerror string is built by a renderer in `cmd/kref` (alongside `formatCLIError`),\nnot in `internal/render` (which stays free of CLI concerns).\n\n### 3.2 Example blocks\n\nEvery leaf command gains an `Example:` field with annotated invocations. The\n`examples` slice in a command's `argGuide` is the same text shown in `--help`,\nso the worked examples in the error and in `--help` never drift. Commands that\ntake no entry reference (and therefore have no `argGuide`) carry an `Example`\nliteral directly.\n\n### 3.3 Safe-read default (most-recent)\n\n`show`, `log`, `diff`, `links`, `tree` change from `ExactArgs(1)` to\n`MaximumNArgs(1)`. With zero args they resolve the target via a new store\nmethod:\n\n```go\n// MostRecent returns the entry with the latest UpdatedAt across all tiers\n// (deleted entries excluded). It returns ErrNoEntries when the store is empty\n// so callers can render a friendly \"create one first\" message.\nfunc (s *Store) MostRecent() (*entry.Snapshot, error)\n```\n\nTies on `UpdatedAt` break deterministically by id (ascending) so repeated runs\nare stable. When the default fires, the command prints a one-line note to\n**stderr** (`cmd.ErrOrStderr()`), suppressed under `--json` so piped stdout\nstays clean:\n\n```\n$ kref show\n(no id given — showing most recent: a1b2c3d4 \"Auth design\")\n\u003cnormal show output on stdout\u003e\n```\n\nAn empty store yields a friendly error: `no entries yet — create one with\n`kref add ...``.\n\n## 4. Per-command audit\n\n| Commands | Today | Change |\n|---|---|---|\n| `show` `log` `diff` `links` `tree` | `ExactArgs(1)` | `MaximumNArgs(1)`; default to most-recent + stderr note; `Example` |\n| `purge` `rm` `restore` `resolve` `edit` `update` `promote` `private` | `ExactArgs(1)`, opaque error | `guidedArgs` actionable error; `Example` |\n| `status` `supersede` `retier` `link add/rm` | `ExactArgs(2)`, opaque error | `guidedArgs` actionable error; `Example` |\n| `label add/rm` | `MinimumNArgs(2)`, opaque error | `guidedArgs` actionable error; `Example` |\n| `ingest` | `MinimumNArgs(1)`, opaque error | `guidedArgs` actionable error (example shows `kref ingest .`); `Example` |\n| `add` `init` `list` `tidy` `remote` `sync(+push/pull)` `hooks(+install/print)` `mcp` `version` | work bare | `Example` only |\n\n## 5. Wording polish (in-scope drive-bys)\n\n- `label` subcommand `Short`s read awkwardly (\"labeled one or more labels on an\n  entry\"). Change to imperative: \"Add one or more labels to an entry\" /\n  \"Remove one or more labels from an entry\". The output verb (\"labeled\" /\n  \"unlabeled\") is unchanged.\n- `ingest` `Short`: \"director(ies)\" → \"directories\".\n\n## 6. Testing\n\nTest-driven, following the existing ginkgo suites:\n\n- **`Store.MostRecent()`** (`internal/store`): returns the latest-`UpdatedAt`\n  entry across tiers; deterministic tie-break; `ErrNoEntries` on an empty store;\n  excludes deleted entries.\n- **CLI** (`cmd/kref`):\n  - A representative destructive command (`purge`) run bare emits an error\n    containing the `find one:`, `then:`, and `example:` guidance.\n  - `show` and `log` run with no id resolve to the most-recent entry; the stderr\n    note names that entry.\n  - `--json` suppresses the recency note (stdout parses as a single JSON value).\n  - `kref \u003ccmd\u003e --help` contains the command's `Example` text for each leaf\n    command (table-driven over the command tree).\n  - Empty-store: `kref show` with no entries returns the friendly \"create one\n    first\" error.\n\n## 7. Risks \u0026 mitigations\n\n- **Most-recent surprises the user.** Mitigated by the explicit stderr note and\n  by restricting the default to read-only commands — nothing is mutated.\n- **Example/usage drift.** Mitigated by sourcing both the error examples and the\n  `--help` examples from the same `argGuide.examples`, and by the table-driven\n  `--help` test.\n- **Scope creep into ergonomics** (editor-on-empty, id-from-cwd). Explicitly\n  deferred in §2 non-goals."}]}